<p><b>Calculus</b> is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathemat=
ics" title=3D"Mathematics">mathematical</a> study of continuous change, in =
the same way that <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry" title=
=3D"Geometry">geometry</a> is the study of shape, and <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebra" title=3D"Algebra">algebra</a> is the study of =
generalizations of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic_oper=
ations" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Arithmetic operations">arithmetic op=
erations</a>.
</p><p>Originally called <b>infinitesimal calculus</b> or "the calculus of =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Infinitesimal" title=3D"Infinitesi=
mal">infinitesimals</a>", it has two major branches, <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Differential_calculus" title=3D"Differential calculus">d=
ifferential calculus</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integ=
ral_calculus" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Integral calculus">integral ca=
lculus</a>. The former concerns instantaneous <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Rate_of_change_(mathematics)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ra=
te of change (mathematics)">rates of change</a>, and the <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slope" title=3D"Slope">slopes</a> of <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Curve" title=3D"Curve">curves</a>, while the latt=
er concerns accumulation of quantities, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Area" title=3D"Area">areas</a> under or between curves. These two=
 branches are related to each other by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Fundamental_theorem_of_calculus" title=3D"Fundamental theorem of c=
alculus">fundamental theorem of calculus</a>. They make use of the fundamen=
tal notions of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convergence_(mathem=
atics)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Convergence (mathematics)">convergen=
ce</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Infinite_sequence" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Infinite sequence">infinite sequences</a> and <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Series_(mathematics)" title=3D"Series=
 (mathematics)">infinite series</a> to a well-defined <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Limit_(mathematics)" title=3D"Limit (mathematics)">limi=
t</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> It is the "mathematical bac=
kbone" for dealing with problems where variables change with time or anothe=
r reference variable.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> It has also =
been called "the basic instrument of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Outline_of_physical_science" title=3D"Outline of physical science">physi=
cal science</a>".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Infinitesimal calculus was formulated separately in the late 17th ce=
ntury by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isaac_Newton" title=3D"Is=
aac Newton">Isaac Newton</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/G=
ottfried_Wilhelm_Leibniz" title=3D"Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz">Gottfried Wil=
helm Leibniz</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus=
#cite_note-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup> Later work, including <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/(%CE%B5,_%CE%B4)-definition_of_limit" class=3D"mw-redirect" ti=
tle=3D"(=CE=B5, =CE=B4)-definition of limit">codifying the idea of limits</=
a>, put these developments on a more solid conceptual footing. The concepts=
 and techniques found in calculus have diverse applications in <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Science" title=3D"Science">science</a>, <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Engineering" title=3D"Engineering">engin=
eering</a>, and other branches of mathematics.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-=
6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
