<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Etymology">Etymology</h2></=
div>
<div class=3D"side-box side-box-right plainlinks sistersitebox"><link rel=
=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r112678840=
9">
<div class=3D"side-box-flex">
<div class=3D"side-box-image"><span class=3D"noviewer" typeof=3D"mw:File"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Wiktionary-logo-en-v2.svg" cla=
ss=3D"mw-file-description"><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.or=
g/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/99/Wiktionary-logo-en-v2.svg/40px-Wiktionary-lo=
go-en-v2.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"40" height=3D"40" class=3D"mw=
-file-element" data-file-width=3D"512" data-file-height=3D"512"></a></span>=
</div>
<div class=3D"side-box-text plainlist">Look up <i><b><a href=3D"https://en.=
wiktionary.org/wiki/Special:Search/calculus" class=3D"extiw" title=3D"wikti=
onary:Special:Search/calculus">calculus</a></b></i> in Wiktionary, the free=
 dictionary.</div></div>
</div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics_education" title=
=3D"Mathematics education">mathematics education</a>, <i>calculus</i> is an=
 abbreviation of both <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Infinitesima=
l_calculus" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Infinitesimal calculus">infinite=
simal calculus</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integral_ca=
lculus" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Integral calculus">integral calculus=
</a>, which denotes courses of elementary <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Mathematical_analysis" title=3D"Mathematical analysis">mathematical=
 analysis</a>.=20
</p><p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Latin" title=3D"Latin">L=
atin</a>, the word <i>calculus</i> means =E2=80=9Csmall pebble=E2=80=9D, (t=
he <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diminutive" title=3D"Diminutive=
">diminutive</a> of <i><a href=3D"https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/calx" clas=
s=3D"extiw" title=3D"wikt:calx">calx</a>,</i> meaning "stone"), a meaning w=
hich still <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus_(medicine)" ti=
tle=3D"Calculus (medicine)">persists in medicine</a>. Because such pebbles =
were used for counting out distances,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-8"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up> tallying votes, and doing <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abac=
us" title=3D"Abacus">abacus</a> arithmetic, the word came to be the Latin w=
ord for <i>calculation</i>. In this sense, it was used in English at least =
as early as 1672, several years before the publications of Leibniz and Newt=
on, who wrote their mathematical texts in Latin.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note=
-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup>
</p><p>In addition to differential calculus and integral calculus, the term=
 is also used for naming specific methods of computation or theories that i=
mply some sort of computation. Examples of this usage include <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Propositional_calculus" class=3D"mw-redirect" t=
itle=3D"Propositional calculus">propositional calculus</a>, <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ricci_calculus" title=3D"Ricci calculus">Ricci ca=
lculus</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus_of_variations=
" title=3D"Calculus of variations">calculus of variations</a>, <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lambda_calculus" title=3D"Lambda calculus">lam=
bda calculus</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sequent_calculus=
" title=3D"Sequent calculus">sequent calculus</a>, and <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Process_calculus" title=3D"Process calculus">process c=
alculus</a>. Furthermore, the term "calculus" has variously been applied in=
 ethics and philosophy, for such systems as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Jeremy_Bentham" title=3D"Jeremy Bentham">Bentham's</a> <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Felicific_calculus" title=3D"Felicific calcu=
lus">felicific calculus</a>, and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Ethical_calculus" title=3D"Ethical calculus">ethical calculus</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_calculus"=
 title=3D"History of calculus">History of calculus</a></div>
<p>Modern calculus was developed in 17th-century Europe by <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isaac_Newton" title=3D"Isaac Newton">Isaac Newton<=
/a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gottfried_Wilhelm_Leibniz"=
 title=3D"Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz">Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz</a> (indepen=
dently of each other, first publishing around the same time). Elements of i=
t first appeared in ancient Egypt and later Greece, then in China and the M=
iddle East, and still later again in medieval Europe and India.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Ancient_precursors">Ancient=
 precursors</h3></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Egypt">Egypt</h4></div>
<p>Calculations of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volume" title=
=3D"Volume">volume</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area" t=
itle=3D"Area">area</a>, one goal of integral calculus, can be found in the =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Egyptian_mathematics" class=3D"mw-=
redirect" title=3D"Egyptian mathematics">Egyptian</a> <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moscow_Mathematical_Papyrus" title=3D"Moscow Mathematic=
al Papyrus">Moscow papyrus</a> (<abbr title=3D"circa">c.</abbr><span style=
=3D"white-space:nowrap;">=E2=80=891820<span class=3D"nowrap">&nbsp;</span>B=
C</span>), but the formulae are simple instructions, with no indication as =
to how they were obtained.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Calculus#cite_note-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Greece">Greece</h4></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greek_mathematics" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Greek mathematics">Greek mathematics</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Parabolic_segment_and_inscrib=
ed_triangle.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.w=
ikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/36/Parabolic_segment_and_inscribed_t=
riangle.svg/250px-Parabolic_segment_and_inscribed_triangle.svg.png" decodin=
g=3D"async" width=3D"190" height=3D"313" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-fil=
e-width=3D"243" data-file-height=3D"400"></a><figcaption>Archimedes used th=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Method_of_exhaustion" title=3D"M=
ethod of exhaustion">method of exhaustion</a> to calculate the area under a=
 parabola in his work <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quadratur=
e_of_the_Parabola" title=3D"Quadrature of the Parabola">Quadrature of the P=
arabola</a></i>.</figcaption></figure>
<p>Laying the foundations for integral calculus and foreshadowing the conce=
pt of the limit, ancient Greek mathematician <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Eudoxus_of_Cnidus" title=3D"Eudoxus of Cnidus">Eudoxus of Cnidus=
</a> (<span title=3D"circa">c.</span><span style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">=
=E2=80=89390=E2=80=93337<span class=3D"nowrap">&nbsp;</span>BC</span>) deve=
loped the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Method_of_exhaustion" ti=
tle=3D"Method of exhaustion">method of exhaustion</a> to prove the formulas=
 for cone and pyramid volumes.
</p><p>During the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hellenistic_peri=
od" title=3D"Hellenistic period">Hellenistic period</a>, this method was fu=
rther developed by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Archimedes" tit=
le=3D"Archimedes">Archimedes</a> (<span title=3D"circa">c.</span><span styl=
e=3D"white-space:nowrap;">=E2=80=89287</span>&nbsp;=E2=80=93 c.<span style=
=3D"white-space:nowrap;">=E2=80=89212</span><span class=3D"nowrap">&nbsp;</=
span>BC), who combined it with a concept of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Cavalieri%27s_principle" title=3D"Cavalieri's principle">indi=
visibles</a>=E2=80=94a precursor to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Archimedes_use_of_infinitesimals" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Archimed=
es use of infinitesimals">infinitesimals</a>=E2=80=94allowing him to solve =
several problems now treated by integral calculus. In <i><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Method_of_Mechanical_Theorems" title=3D"The Meth=
od of Mechanical Theorems">The Method of Mechanical Theorems</a></i> he des=
cribes, for example, calculating the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Center_of_gravity" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Center of gravity">cen=
ter of gravity</a> of a solid <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sphe=
re" title=3D"Sphere">hemisphere</a>, the center of gravity of a <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frustum" title=3D"Frustum">frustum</a> of a c=
