<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Europe">Europe</h4></div>
<p>The mathematical study of continuity was revived in the 14th century by =
the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oxford_Calculators" title=3D"O=
xford Calculators">Oxford Calculators</a> and French collaborators such as =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nicole_Oresme" title=3D"Nicole Ore=
sme">Nicole Oresme</a>. They proved the "Merton <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Mean_speed_theorem" title=3D"Mean speed theorem">mean speed t=
heorem</a>": that a uniformly accelerated body travels the same distance as=
 a body with uniform speed whose speed is half the final velocity of the ac=
celerated body.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-22" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Modern">Modern</h3></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Johannes_Kepler" title=3D"Johan=
nes Kepler">Johannes Kepler</a>'s work <i>Stereometria Doliorum</i> (1615) =
formed the basis of integral calculus.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-23" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-23"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> Kepler developed a method to calculate the area of an ellipse by ad=
ding up the lengths of many radii drawn from a focus of the ellipse.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-EB1911_24-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-EB1911-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Significant work was performed in a treatise, the origin being Keple=
r's methods,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-EB1911_24-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-EB1911-24"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> wr=
itten by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bonaventura_Cavalieri" ti=
tle=3D"Bonaventura Cavalieri">Bonaventura Cavalieri</a>, who argued that vo=
lumes and areas should be computed as the sums of the volumes and areas of =
infinitesimally thin cross-sections. The ideas were similar to Archimedes' =
in <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Method_of_Mechanical_The=
orems" title=3D"The Method of Mechanical Theorems">The Method</a></i>, but =
this treatise is believed to have been lost in the 13th century and was onl=
y rediscovered in the early 20th century, and so would have been unknown to=
 Cavalieri. Cavalieri's work was not well respected since his methods could=
 lead to erroneous results, and the infinitesimal quantities he introduced =
were disreputable at first.
</p><p>The formal study of calculus brought together Cavalieri's infinitesi=
mals with the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus_of_finite_d=
ifferences" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Calculus of finite differences">=
calculus of finite differences</a> developed in Europe at around the same t=
ime. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pierre_de_Fermat" title=3D"Pi=
erre de Fermat">Pierre de Fermat</a>, claiming that he borrowed from <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diophantus" title=3D"Diophantus">Diophan=
tus</a>, introduced the concept of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Adequality" title=3D"Adequality">adequality</a>, which represented equalit=
y up to an infinitesimal error term.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-25" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-25"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup> The combination was achieved by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/John_Wallis" title=3D"John Wallis">John Wallis</a>, <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isaac_Barrow" title=3D"Isaac Barrow">Isaac Barrow</a>=
, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Gregory_(astronomer_an=
d_mathematician)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"James Gregory (astronomer =
and mathematician)">James Gregory</a>, the latter two proving themselves to=
 be predecessors to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fundamenta=
l_theorem_of_calculus" title=3D"Fundamental theorem of calculus">second fun=
damental theorem of calculus</a> around 1670.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-26" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-=
26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-27" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Product_rule" title=3D"=
Product rule">product rule</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Chain_rule" title=3D"Chain rule">chain rule</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-28" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_no=
te-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup> the notions of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Higher_derivative" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Higher derivative">higher=
 derivatives</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taylor_series=
" title=3D"Taylor series">Taylor series</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-29" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-=
29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> and of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_fu=
nction" title=3D"Analytic function">analytic functions</a><sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-30" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculu=
s#cite_note-30"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> were used by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Isaac_Newton" title=3D"Isaac Newton">Isaac Newton</a> in an idiosync=
ratic notation which he applied to solve problems of <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_physics" title=3D"Mathematical physics">mat=
hematical physics</a>. In his works, Newton rephrased his ideas to suit the=
 mathematical idiom of the time, replacing calculations with infinitesimals=
 by equivalent geometrical arguments which were considered beyond reproach.=
 He used the methods of calculus to solve the problem of planetary motion, =
the shape of the surface of a rotating fluid, the oblateness of the earth, =
the motion of a weight sliding on a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Cycloid" title=3D"Cycloid">cycloid</a>, and many other problems discussed=
 in his <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philosophi%C3%A6_Natura=
lis_Principia_Mathematica" title=3D"Philosophi=C3=A6 Naturalis Principia Ma=
thematica">Principia Mathematica</a></i> (1687). In other work, he develope=
d series expansions for functions, including fractional and irrational powe=
rs, and it was clear that he understood the principles of the <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taylor_series" title=3D"Taylor series">Taylor s=
eries</a>. He did not publish all these discoveries, and at this time infin=
itesimal methods were still considered disreputable.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Lan=
dmark_31-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ca=
lculus#cite_note-Landmark-31"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1273380762/mw-parser-output/.tmulti"><div class=3D"thumb tmulti tright"><di=
