ied_Wilhelm_Leibniz,_Bernhard_Christoph_Francke.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-descr=
iption"><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons=
/thumb/c/ce/Gottfried_Wilhelm_Leibniz%2C_Bernhard_Christoph_Francke.jpg/250=
px-Gottfried_Wilhelm_Leibniz%2C_Bernhard_Christoph_Francke.jpg" decoding=3D=
"async" width=3D"167" height=3D"206" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-wi=
dth=3D"4486" data-file-height=3D"5538"></a></span></div><div class=3D"thumb=
caption"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gottfried_Wilhelm_Leibniz=
" title=3D"Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz">Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz</a> was the=
 first to state clearly the rules of calculus.</div></div><div class=3D"tsi=
ngle" style=3D"width:149px;max-width:149px"><div class=3D"thumbimage" style=
=3D"height:206px;overflow:hidden"><span typeof=3D"mw:File"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:GodfreyKneller-IsaacNewton-1689.jpg" class=3D=
"mw-file-description"><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wik=
ipedia/commons/thumb/3/39/GodfreyKneller-IsaacNewton-1689.jpg/250px-Godfrey=
Kneller-IsaacNewton-1689.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"147" height=3D"20=
6" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"1364" data-file-height=3D"1=
916"></a></span></div><div class=3D"thumbcaption"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Isaac_Newton" title=3D"Isaac Newton">Isaac Newton</a> devel=
oped the use of calculus in his <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ne=
wton%27s_laws_of_motion" title=3D"Newton's laws of motion">laws of motion</=
a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Newton%27s_law_of_universal=
_gravitation" title=3D"Newton's law of universal gravitation">universal gra=
vitation</a>.</div></div></div></div></div>
<p>These ideas were arranged into a true calculus of infinitesimals by <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gottfried_Wilhelm_Leibniz" title=3D"Go=
ttfried Wilhelm Leibniz">Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz</a>, who was originally =
accused of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plagiarism" title=3D"Pl=
agiarism">plagiarism</a> by Newton.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-leib_32-0" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-leib=
-32"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup> He is now regarded as an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Multiple_discovery" title=3D"Multiple discovery">independent invent=
or</a> of and contributor to calculus. His contribution was to provide a cl=
ear set of rules for working with infinitesimal quantities, allowing the co=
mputation of second and higher derivatives, and providing the <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Product_rule" title=3D"Product rule">product ru=
le</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chain_rule" title=3D"Ch=
ain rule">chain rule</a>, in their differential and integral forms. Unlike =
Newton, Leibniz put painstaking effort into his choices of notation.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-33" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Calculus#cite_note-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>33<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Today, Leibniz and Newton are usually both given credit for independ=
ently inventing and developing calculus. Newton was the first to apply calc=
ulus to general <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Physics" title=3D"=
Physics">physics</a>. Leibniz developed much of the notation used in calcul=
us today.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-TMU_34-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-TMU-34"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=
=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Pages: 51=E2=80=9352">:=E2=80=8A51=E2=
=80=9352=E2=80=8A</span></sup> The basic insights that both Newton and Leib=
niz provided led to their development of the laws of differentiation and in=
tegration, their emphasis that differentiation and integration are inverse =
processes, their development of methods for calculating the second and high=
er derivatives, and their statement of the notion for approximating a polyn=
omial series.
</p><p>When Newton and Leibniz first published their results, there was <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Newton_v._Leibniz_calculus_controvers=
y" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Newton v. Leibniz calculus controversy">g=
reat controversy</a> over which mathematician (and therefore which country)=
 deserved credit. Newton derived his results first (later to be published i=
n his <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Method_of_Fluxions" title=
=3D"Method of Fluxions">Method of Fluxions</a></i>), but Leibniz published =
his "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nova_Methodus_pro_Maximis_et_=
Minimis" title=3D"Nova Methodus pro Maximis et Minimis">Nova Methodus pro M=
aximis et Minimis</a>" first. Newton claimed Leibniz stole ideas from his u=
npublished notes, which Newton had shared with a few members of the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Royal_Society" title=3D"Royal Society">Ro=
yal Society</a>. This controversy divided English-speaking mathematicians f=
rom continental European mathematicians for many years, to the detriment of=
 English mathematics.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-35" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-35"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A careful=
 examination of the papers of Leibniz and Newton shows that they arrived at=
 their results independently, with Leibniz starting first with integration =
and Newton with differentiation. It is Leibniz, however, who gave the new d=
iscipline its name. Newton called his calculus "<a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Method_of_fluxions" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Method of =
fluxions">the science of fluxions</a>", a term that endured in English scho=
ols into the 19th century.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-36" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-36"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>36<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup =
class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page / location: 100">:=E2=80=8A1=
00=E2=80=8A</span></sup> The first complete treatise on calculus to be writ=
ten in English and use the Leibniz notation was not published until 1815.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-37" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-37"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>37<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Maria_Gaetana_Agnesi.jpg" cla=
ss=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikiped=
ia/commons/thumb/5/57/Maria_Gaetana_Agnesi.jpg/250px-Maria_Gaetana_Agnesi.j=
pg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"190" height=3D"221" class=3D"mw-file-elemen=
t" data-file-width=3D"344" data-file-height=3D"400"></a><figcaption><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maria_Gaetana_Agnesi" title=3D"Maria Gaet=
ana Agnesi">Maria Gaetana Agnesi</a></figcaption></figure>
<p>Since the time of Leibniz and Newton, many mathematicians have contribut=
ed to the continuing development of calculus. One of the first and most com=
plete works on both infinitesimal and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Integral_calculus" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Integral calculus">in=
tegral calculus</a> was written in 1748 by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Maria_Gaetana_Agnesi" title=3D"Maria Gaetana Agnesi">Maria Gaetana=
 Agnesi</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-38" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-38"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>38<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-39" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#=
cite_note-39"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>39<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Foundations">Foundations</h=
3></div>
<p>In calculus, <i>foundations</i> refers to the <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Rigorous#Mathematical_rigor" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
Rigorous">rigorous</a> development of the subject from <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Axiom" title=3D"Axiom">axioms</a> and definitions. In =
early calculus, the use of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Infinit=
esimal" title=3D"Infinitesimal">infinitesimal</a> quantities was thought un=
rigorous and was fiercely criticized by several authors, most notably <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michel_Rolle" title=3D"Michel Rolle">Mi=
chel Rolle</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Berkeley=
" title=3D"George Berkeley">Bishop Berkeley</a>. Berkeley famously describe=
d infinitesimals as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ghosts_of_=
departed_quantities" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ghosts of departed quan=
tities">ghosts of departed quantities</a> in his book <i><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Analyst" title=3D"The Analyst">The Analyst</a></=
i> in 1734. Working out a rigorous foundation for calculus occupied mathema=
ticians for much of the century following Newton and Leibniz.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-Bell-SEP_40-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-Bell-SEP-40"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>40<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Several mathematicians, including <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Colin_Maclaurin" title=3D"Colin Maclaurin">Maclaurin</a>, tried to p=
rove the soundness of using infinitesimals, but it would not be until 150 y=
ears later when, due to the work of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Augustin-Louis_Cauchy" title=3D"Augustin-Louis Cauchy">Cauchy</a> and <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karl_Weierstrass" title=3D"Karl Weier=
strass">Weierstrass</a>, a way was finally found to avoid mere "notions" of=
 infinitely small quantities.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-41" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-41"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>41<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 The foundations of differential and integral calculus had been laid. In Ca=
uchy's <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cours_d%27Analyse" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Cours d'Analyse">Cours d'Analyse</a></i>, we find=
 a broad range of foundational approaches, including a definition of <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Continuous_function" title=3D"Continuous=
 function">continuity</a> in terms of infinitesimals, and a (somewhat impre=
cise) prototype of an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/(%CE%B5,_%CE=
%B4)-definition_of_limit" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"(=CE=B5, =CE=B4)-d=
efinition of limit">(=CE=B5, =CE=B4)-definition of limit</a> in the definit=
ion of differentiation.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-42" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-42"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>42<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In his=
 work, Weierstrass formalized the concept of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Limit_of_a_function" title=3D"Limit of a function">limit</a> and=
 eliminated infinitesimals (although his definition can validate <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nilsquare" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ni=
lsquare">nilsquare</a> infinitesimals). Following the work of Weierstrass, =
it eventually became common to base calculus on limits instead of infinites=
imal quantities, though the subject is still occasionally called "infinites=
imal calculus". <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bernhard_Riemann" =
title=3D"Bernhard Riemann">Bernhard Riemann</a> used these ideas to give a =
precise definition of the integral.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-43" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-43"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>43<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup> It was also during this period that the ideas of calculus were general=
ized to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_plane" title=
=3D"Complex plane">complex plane</a> with the development of <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_analysis" title=3D"Complex analysis">com=
plex analysis</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-44" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-44"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>44<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In modern mathematics, the foundations of calculus are included in t=
he field of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_analysis" title=
=3D"Real analysis">real analysis</a>, which contains full definitions and <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_proof" title=3D"Mathem=
atical proof">proofs</a> of the theorems of calculus. The reach of calculus=
 has also been greatly extended. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/H=
enri_Lebesgue" title=3D"Henri Lebesgue">Henri Lebesgue</a> invented <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Measure_theory" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"Measure theory">measure theory</a>, based on earlier developments by =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89mile_Borel" title=3D"=C3=89m=
ile Borel">=C3=89mile Borel</a>, and used it to define integrals of all but=
 the most <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pathological_(mathematic=
s)" title=3D"Pathological (mathematics)">pathological</a> functions.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-45" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Calculus#cite_note-45"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>45<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Laurent_Schwartz" title=3D"Laurent Schwartz">Laurent Schwartz</a> intro=
duced <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Distribution_(mathematics)" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Distribution (mathematics)">distributions</a=
>, which can be used to take the derivative of any function whatsoever.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-46" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-46"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>46<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Limits are not the only rigorous approach to the foundation of calcu=
lus. Another way is to use <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abraham=
_Robinson" title=3D"Abraham Robinson">Abraham Robinson</a>'s <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Non-standard_analysis" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"Non-standard analysis">non-standard analysis</a>. Robinson's approach=
, developed in the 1960s, uses technical machinery from <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_logic" title=3D"Mathematical logic">math=
ematical logic</a> to augment the real number system with <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Infinitesimal" title=3D"Infinitesimal">infinitesima=
l</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Infinity" title=3D"Infin=
ity">infinite</a> numbers, as in the original Newton-Leibniz conception. Th=
e resulting numbers are called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyp=
erreal_number" title=3D"Hyperreal number">hyperreal numbers</a>, and they c=
an be used to give a Leibniz-like development of the usual rules of calculu=
s.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-47" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-47"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>47<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> There is also <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Smooth_infinitesimal_analysis" title=3D"Smooth i=
nfinitesimal analysis">smooth infinitesimal analysis</a>, which differs fro=
m non-standard analysis in that it mandates neglecting higher-power infinit=
esimals during derivations.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Bell-SEP_40-1" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-Bell-SEP=
-40"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>40<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup> Based on the ideas of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/F._W._Lawvere" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"F. W. Lawvere">F. W. Law=
vere</a> and employing the methods of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Category_theory" title=3D"Category theory">category theory</a>, smooth =
infinitesimal analysis views all functions as being <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Continuous_function" title=3D"Continuous function">contin=
uous</a> and incapable of being expressed in terms of <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Discrete_mathematics" title=3D"Discrete mathematics">di=
screte</a> entities. One aspect of this formulation is that the <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Law_of_excluded_middle" title=3D"Law of exclu=
ded middle">law of excluded middle</a> does not hold.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Be=
ll-SEP_40-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C=
alculus#cite_note-Bell-SEP-40"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>40<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The law of excluded middle is al=
so rejected in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Constructive_mathem=
atics" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Constructive mathematics">constructiv=
e mathematics</a>, a branch of mathematics that insists that proofs of the =
existence of a number, function, or other mathematical object should give a=
 construction of the object. Reformulations of calculus in a constructive f=
ramework are generally part of the subject of <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Constructive_analysis" title=3D"Constructive analysis">construc=
tive analysis</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Bell-SEP_40-3" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-Bell-SEP-40"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>40<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Significance">Significance<=
/h3></div>
<p>While many of the ideas of calculus had been developed earlier in <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greek_mathematics" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"Greek mathematics">Greece</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Chinese_mathematics" title=3D"Chinese mathematics">China</a>, <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indian_mathematics" title=3D"Indian math=
ematics">India</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Islamic_mathem=
atics" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Islamic mathematics">Iraq, Persia</a>=
, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Japanese_mathematics" title=
=3D"Japanese mathematics">Japan</a>, the use of calculus began in Europe, d=
uring the 17th century, when Newton and Leibniz built on the work of earlie=
r mathematicians to introduce its basic principles.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_1=
4-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#=
cite_note-:0-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Landmark_31-1" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-Landmar=
k-31"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-48" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-48"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>48<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The Hungarian=
 polymath <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_von_Neumann" title=
=3D"John von Neumann">John von Neumann</a> wrote of this work,
</p>
<blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p>The calculus was the first achieveme=
nt of modern mathematics and it is difficult to overestimate its importance=
. I think it defines more unequivocally than anything else the inception of=
 modern mathematics, and the system of mathematical analysis, which is its =
logical development, still constitutes the greatest technical advance in ex=
act thinking.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-49" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-49"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>49<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></p></blockquote>
<p>Applications of differential calculus include computations involving <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Velocity" title=3D"Velocity">velocity=
</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acceleration" title=3D"Ac=
celeration">acceleration</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Slope" title=3D"Slope">slope</a> of a curve, and <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_optimization" title=3D"Mathematical optimizatio=
n">optimization</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:5_50-0" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-:5-50"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>50<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><su=
p class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Pages: 341=E2=80=93453">:=E2=80=
=8A341=E2=80=93453=E2=80=8A</span></sup> Applications of integral calculus =
include computations involving area, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Volume" title=3D"Volume">volume</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Arc_length" title=3D"Arc length">arc length</a>, <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Center_of_mass" title=3D"Center of mass">center of mas=
s</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Work_(physics)" title=3D"Wo=
rk (physics)">work</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pressu=
re" title=3D"Pressure">pressure</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:5_50-1" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-:5-50=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>50<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Pages: 685=E2=
=80=93700">:=E2=80=8A685=E2=80=93700=E2=80=8A</span></sup> More advanced ap=
plications include <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Power_series" t=
itle=3D"Power series">power series</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Fourier_series" title=3D"Fourier series">Fourier series</a>.
</p><p>Calculus is also used to gain a more precise understanding of the na=
ture of space, time, and motion. For centuries, mathematicians and philosop=
hers wrestled with paradoxes involving <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Division_by_zero" title=3D"Division by zero">division by zero</a> or s=
ums of infinitely many numbers. These questions arise in the study of <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Motion_(physics)" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"Motion (physics)">motion</a> and area. The <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancient_Greek" title=3D"Ancient Greek">ancient Greek</a>=
 philosopher <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zeno_of_Elea" title=
=3D"Zeno of Elea">Zeno of Elea</a> gave several famous examples of such <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zeno%27s_paradoxes" title=3D"Zeno's p=
aradoxes">paradoxes</a>. Calculus provides tools, especially the <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Limit_(mathematics)" title=3D"Limit (mathema=
tics)">limit</a> and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Infinite_=
series" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Infinite series">infinite series</a>=
, that resolve the paradoxes.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-51" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-51"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>51<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Principles">Principles</h2>=
</div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Limits_and_infinitesimals">=
Limits and infinitesimals</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main articles: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Limit_of_a_function=
" title=3D"Limit of a function">Limit of a function</a> and <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Infinitesimal" title=3D"Infinitesimal">Infinitesi=
mal</a></div>
<p>Calculus is usually developed by working with very small quantities. His=
torically, the first method of doing so was by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Infinitesimal" title=3D"Infinitesimal">infinitesimals</a>. The=
se are objects which can be treated like real numbers but which are, in som=
e sense, "infinitely small". For example, an infinitesimal number could be =
greater than 0, but less than any number in the sequence 1, 1/2, 1/3, ... a=
nd thus less than any positive <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rea=
l_number" title=3D"Real number">real number</a>. From this point of view, c=
alculus is a collection of techniques for manipulating infinitesimals. The =
symbols <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e dx}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>d</mi>
        <mi>x</mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle dx}</annotati=
on>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/845c817e348381a13f3fad5184169ce0e021c685" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:2.546ex; height:2.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle dx}=
"></span> and <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><spa=
n class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: n=
one;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displ=
aystyle dy}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>d</mi>
        <mi>y</mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle dy}</annotati=
on>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/5c5eda9ec854eb0076d43c147eb8956637a1003f" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.671ex; width:2.371ex; height:2.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle dy}=
"></span> were taken to be infinitesimal, and the derivative <span class=3D=
"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-i=
nline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://=
www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle dy/dx}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>d</mi>
        <mi>y</mi>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mo>/</mo>
        </mrow>
        <mi>d</mi>
        <mi>x</mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle dy/dx}</annot=
ation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/add69069028cada9be6b945dd4b9895e3ff2fd23" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:6.079ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle dy/=
dx}"></span> was their ratio.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Bell-SEP_40-4" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-Bell-S=
EP-40"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>40<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The infinitesimal approach fell out of favor in the 19th century bec=
ause it was difficult to make the notion of an infinitesimal precise. In th=
e late 19th century, infinitesimals were replaced within academia by the <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Epsilon,_delta" class=3D"mw-redirect=
" title=3D"Epsilon, delta">epsilon, delta</a> approach to <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Limit_of_a_function" title=3D"Limit of a function">=
limits</a>. Limits describe the behavior of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Function_(mathematics)" title=3D"Function (mathematics)">functi=
on</a> at a certain input in terms of its values at nearby inputs. They cap=
ture small-scale behavior using the intrinsic structure of the <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_number" title=3D"Real number">real number=
 system</a> (as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metric_space" ti=
tle=3D"Metric space">metric space</a> with the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Least-upper-bound_property" title=3D"Least-upper-bound propert=
y">least-upper-bound property</a>). In this treatment, calculus is a collec=
tion of techniques for manipulating certain limits. Infinitesimals get repl=
aced by sequences of smaller and smaller numbers, and the infinitely small =
behavior of a function is found by taking the limiting behavior for these s=
equences. Limits were thought to provide a more rigorous foundation for cal=
culus, and for this reason, they became the standard approach during the 20=
th century. However, the infinitesimal concept was revived in the 20th cent=
ury with the introduction of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Non-s=
tandard_analysis" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Non-standard analysis">non=
-standard analysis</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Smooth_=
infinitesimal_analysis" title=3D"Smooth infinitesimal analysis">smooth infi=
nitesimal analysis</a>, which provided solid foundations for the manipulati=
on of infinitesimals.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Bell-SEP_40-5" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-Bell-SEP-40"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>40<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Differential_calculus">Diff=
erential calculus</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Differential_calculu=
s" title=3D"Differential calculus">Differential calculus</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Tangent_line_to_a_curve.svg" class=3D"mw-file=
-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/th=
umb/0/05/Tangent_line_to_a_curve.svg/500px-Tangent_line_to_a_curve.svg.png"=
 decoding=3D"async" width=3D"340" height=3D"237" class=3D"mw-file-element" =
data-file-width=3D"319" data-file-height=3D"222"></a><figcaption>Tangent li=
ne at <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>x</i><sub>0</sub>, <i>f</i>(<i>x</i><sub>=
0</sub>))</span>. The derivative <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f=E2=80=B2</i>(=
<i>x</i>)</span> of a curve at a point is the slope (rise over run) of the =
line tangent to that curve at that point.</figcaption></figure>
<p>Differential calculus is the study of the definition, properties, and ap=
plications of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Derivative" titl=
e=3D"Derivative">derivative</a> of a function. The process of finding the d=
erivative is called <i>differentiation</i>. Given a function and a point in=
 the domain, the derivative at that point is a way of encoding the small-sc=
ale behavior of the function near that point. By finding the derivative of =
a function at every point in its domain, it is possible to produce a new fu=
nction, called the <i>derivative function</i> or just the <i>derivative</i>=
 of the original function. In formal terms, the derivative is a <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_operator" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Linear operator">linear operator</a> which takes a function as its inpu=
t and produces a second function as its output. This is more abstract than =
many of the processes studied in elementary algebra, where functions usuall=
y input a number and output another number. For example, if the doubling fu=
nction is given the input three, then it outputs six, and if the squaring f=
unction is given the input three, then it outputs nine. The derivative, how=
ever, can take the squaring function as an input. This means that the deriv=
ative takes all the information of the squaring function=E2=80=94such as th=
at two is sent to four, three is sent to nine, four is sent to sixteen, and=
 so on=E2=80=94and uses this information to produce another function. The f=
unction produced by differentiating the squaring function turns out to be t=
he doubling function.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-TMU_34-1" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-TMU-34"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
<sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page / location: 32">:=E2=80=
=8A32=E2=80=8A</span></sup>
</p><p>In more explicit terms the "doubling function" may be denoted by <sp=
an class=3D"texhtml"><i>g</i>(<i>x</i>) =3D 2<i>x</i></span> and the "squar=
ing function" by <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i>(<i>x</i>) =3D <i>x</i><su=
p>2</sup></span>. The "derivative" now takes the function <span class=3D"te=
xhtml"><i>f</i>(<i>x</i>)</span>, defined by the expression "<span class=3D=
"texhtml"><i>x</i><sup>2</sup></span>", as an input, that is all the inform=
ation=E2=80=94such as that two is sent to four, three is sent to nine, four=
 is sent to sixteen, and so on=E2=80=94and uses this information to output =
another function, the function <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>g</i>(<i>x</i>) =
=3D 2<i>x</i></span>, as will turn out.
</p><p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lagrange%27s_notation" c=
lass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Lagrange's notation">Lagrange's notation</a>,=
 the symbol for a derivative is an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Apostrophe" title=3D"Apostrophe">apostrophe</a>-like mark called a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_(symbol)" title=3D"Prime (symbol)">=
prime</a>. Thus, the derivative of a function called <span class=3D"texhtml=
"><i>f</i></span> is denoted by <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f=E2=80=B2</i></=
span>, pronounced "f prime" or "f dash". For instance, if <span class=3D"te=
xhtml"><i>f</i>(<i>x</i>) =3D <i>x</i><sup>2</sup></span> is the squaring f=
unction, then <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f=E2=80=B2</i>(<i>x</i>) =3D 2<i>x=
</i></span> is its derivative (the doubling function <span class=3D"texhtml=
"><i>g</i></span> from above).
</p><p>If the input of the function represents time, then the derivative re=
presents change concerning time. For example, if <span class=3D"texhtml"><i=
>f</i></span> is a function that takes time as input and gives the position=
 of a ball at that time as output, then the derivative of <span class=3D"te=
xhtml"><i>f</i></span> is how the position is changing in time, that is, it=
 is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Velocity" title=3D"Velocit=
y">velocity</a> of the ball.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-TMU_34-2" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-TMU-34"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page / location: 18=
=E2=80=9320">:=E2=80=8A18=E2=80=9320=E2=80=8A</span></sup>
</p><p>If a function is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_fun=
ction" title=3D"Linear function">linear</a> (that is if the <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graph_of_a_function" title=3D"Graph of a function=
">graph</a> of the function is a straight line), then the function can be w=
ritten as <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>y</i> =3D <i>mx</i> + <i>b</i></span>,=
 where <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i></span> is the independent variable,=
 <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>y</i></span> is the dependent variable, <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i></span> is the <i>y</i>-intercept, and:
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e m=3D{\frac {\text{rise}}{\text{run}}}=3D{\frac {{\text{change in }}y}{{\t=
ext{change in }}x}}=3D{\frac {\Delta y}{\Delta x}}.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>m</mi>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mtext>rise</mtext>
            <mtext>run</mtext>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mrow>
              <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mtext>change in&nbsp;</mtext>
              </mrow>
              <mi>y</mi>
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mtext>change in&nbsp;</mtext>
              </mrow>
              <mi>x</mi>
            </mrow>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mrow>
              <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=CE=94<!-- =CE=94 --></mi>
              <mi>y</mi>
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=CE=94<!-- =CE=94 --></mi>
              <mi>x</mi>
            </mrow>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle m=3D{\frac {\=
text{rise}}{\text{run}}}=3D{\frac {{\text{change in }}y}{{\text{change in }=
}x}}=3D{\frac {\Delta y}{\Delta x}}.}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/313c6a18c1b2ec00c8ae723e70d431b0037382aa" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -2.338ex; width:32.669ex; height:6.009ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle m=
=3D{\frac {\text{rise}}{\text{run}}}=3D{\frac {{\text{change in }}y}{{\text=
{change in }}x}}=3D{\frac {\Delta y}{\Delta x}}.}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>This gives an exact value for the slope of a straight line.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-:4_52-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Calculus#cite_note-:4-52"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>52<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><spa=
n title=3D"Page: 6">:=E2=80=8A6=E2=80=8A</span></sup> If the graph of the f=
unction is not a straight line, however, then the change in <span class=3D"=
texhtml"><i>y</i></span> divided by the change in <span class=3D"texhtml"><=
i>x</i></span> varies. Derivatives give an exact meaning to the notion of c=
hange in output concerning change in input. To be concrete, let <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i></span> be a function, and fix a point <span class=3D"=
texhtml"><i>a</i></span> in the domain of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i><=
/span>. <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>a</i>, <i>f</i>(<i>a</i>))</span> is a =
point on the graph of the function. If <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>h</i></sp=
an> is a number close to zero, then <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i> + <i>h=
</i></span> is a number close to <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span>. T=
herefore, <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>a</i> + <i>h</i>, <i>f</i>(<i>a</i> +=
 <i>h</i>))</span> is close to <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>a</i>, <i>f</i>(=
<i>a</i>))</span>. The slope between these two points is
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e m=3D{\frac {f(a+h)-f(a)}{(a+h)-a}}=3D{\frac {f(a+h)-f(a)}{h}}.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>m</mi>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mrow>
              <mi>f</mi>
              <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
              <mi>a</mi>
              <mo>+</mo>
              <mi>h</mi>
              <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
              <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
              <mi>f</mi>
              <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
              <mi>a</mi>
              <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
              <mi>a</mi>
              <mo>+</mo>
              <mi>h</mi>
              <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
              <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
              <mi>a</mi>
            </mrow>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mrow>
              <mi>f</mi>
              <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
              <mi>a</mi>
              <mo>+</mo>
              <mi>h</mi>
              <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
              <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
              <mi>f</mi>
              <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
              <mi>a</mi>
              <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
            </mrow>
            <mi>h</mi>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle m=3D{\frac {f=
(a+h)-f(a)}{(a+h)-a}}=3D{\frac {f(a+h)-f(a)}{h}}.}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/e2017cd12adcbfa0f07bcc1090006133781fff8f" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -2.671ex; width:41.867ex; height:6.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle m=
=3D{\frac {f(a+h)-f(a)}{(a+h)-a}}=3D{\frac {f(a+h)-f(a)}{h}}.}"></span></dd=
></dl>
<p>This expression is called a <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Difference_quotient" title=3D"Difference quotient">difference quotient</a><=
/i>. A line through two points on a curve is called a <i>secant line</i>, s=
o <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>m</i></span> is the slope of the secant line b=
etween <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>a</i>, <i>f</i>(<i>a</i>))</span> and <s=
pan class=3D"texhtml">(<i>a</i> + <i>h</i>, <i>f</i>(<i>a</i> + <i>h</i>))<=
/span>. The second line is only an approximation to the behavior of the fun=
ction at the point <span class=3D"texhtml"><i> a</i></span> because it does=
 not account for what happens between <span class=3D"texhtml"><i> a</i></sp=
an> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i> a</i> + <i>h</i></span>. It is not poss=
ible to discover the behavior at <span class=3D"texhtml"><i> a</i></span> b=
y setting <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>h</i></span> to zero because this woul=
d require <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dividing_by_zero" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Dividing by zero">dividing by zero</a>, which is =
undefined. The derivative is defined by taking the <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Limit_(mathematics)" title=3D"Limit (mathematics)">limit</=
a> as <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>h</i></span> tends to zero, meaning that i=
t considers the behavior of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i></span> for all=
 small values of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>h</i></span> and extracts a con=
sistent value for the case when <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>h</i></span> equ=
als zero:
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e \lim _{h\to 0}{f(a+h)-f(a) \over {h}}.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <munder>
          <mo movablelimits=3D"true" form=3D"prefix">lim</mo>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>h</mi>
            <mo stretchy=3D"false">=E2=86=92<!-- =E2=86=92 --></mo>
            <mn>0</mn>
          </mrow>
        </munder>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mrow>
              <mi>f</mi>
              <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
              <mi>a</mi>
              <mo>+</mo>
              <mi>h</mi>
              <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
              <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
              <mi>f</mi>
              <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
              <mi>a</mi>
              <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
            </mrow>
            <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
              <mi>h</mi>
            </mrow>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \lim _{h\to 0=
}{f(a+h)-f(a) \over {h}}.}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/3b3d79e9ff8acf531bb7596a6e0687fbb8027ffb" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -2.005ex; width:20.937ex; height:5.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \l=
im _{h\to 0}{f(a+h)-f(a) \over {h}}.}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>Geometrically, the derivative is the slope of the <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Tangent_line" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Tangent lin=
e">tangent line</a> to the graph of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i></span>=
 at <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span>. The tangent line is a limit of=
 secant lines just as the derivative is a limit of difference quotients. Fo=
r this reason, the derivative is sometimes called the slope of the function=
 <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i></span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:4_52-1" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-=
:4-52"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>52<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Pages: 61=
=E2=80=9363">:=E2=80=8A61=E2=80=9363=E2=80=8A</span></sup>
</p><p>Here is a particular example, the derivative of the squaring functio=
n at the input 3. Let <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i>(<i>x</i>) =3D <i>x</=
i><sup>2</sup></span> be the squaring function.
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Sec2tan.gif" class=3D"mw-file-description"><i=
mg src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/34/Sec2tan=
.gif/500px-Sec2tan.gif" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"340" height=3D"328" cla=
ss=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"586" data-file-height=3D"565"></a=
><figcaption>The derivative <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f=E2=80=B2</i>(<i>x<=
/i>)</span> of a curve at a point is the slope of the line tangent to that =
curve at that point. This slope is determined by considering the limiting v=
alue of the slopes of the second lines. Here the function involved (drawn i=
n red) is <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i>(<i>x</i>) =3D <i>x</i><sup>3</su=
p> =E2=88=92 <i>x</i></span>. The tangent line (in green) which passes thro=
ugh the point <span class=3D"nowrap">(=E2=88=923/2, =E2=88=9215/8)</span> h=
as a slope of 23/4. The vertical and horizontal scales in this image are di=
fferent.</figcaption></figure>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e {\begin{aligned}f'(3)&amp;=3D\lim _{h\to 0}{(3+h)^{2}-3^{2} \over {h}}\\&=
amp;=3D\lim _{h\to 0}{9+6h+h^{2}-9 \over {h}}\\&amp;=3D\lim _{h\to 0}{6h+h^=
{2} \over {h}}\\&amp;=3D\lim _{h\to 0}(6+h)\\&amp;=3D6\end{aligned}}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mtable columnalign=3D"right left right left right left right lef=
t right left right left" rowspacing=3D"3pt" columnspacing=3D"0em 2em 0em 2e=
m 0em 2em 0em 2em 0em 2em 0em" displaystyle=3D"true">
            <mtr>
              <mtd>
                <msup>
                  <mi>f</mi>
                  <mo>=E2=80=B2</mo>
                </msup>
                <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
                <mn>3</mn>
                <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
              </mtd>
              <mtd>
                <mi></mi>
                <mo>=3D</mo>
                <munder>
                  <mo movablelimits=3D"true" form=3D"prefix">lim</mo>
                  <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                    <mi>h</mi>
                    <mo stretchy=3D"false">=E2=86=92<!-- =E2=86=92 --></mo>
                    <mn>0</mn>
                  </mrow>
                </munder>
                <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                  <mfrac>
                    <mrow>
                      <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
                      <mn>3</mn>
                      <mo>+</mo>
                      <mi>h</mi>
                      <msup>
                        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
                        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                          <mn>2</mn>
                        </mrow>
                      </msup>
                      <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
                      <msup>
                        <mn>3</mn>
                        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                          <mn>2</mn>
                        </mrow>
                      </msup>
                    </mrow>
                    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                      <mi>h</mi>
                    </mrow>
                  </mfrac>
                </mrow>
              </mtd>
            </mtr>
            <mtr>
              <mtd></mtd>
              <mtd>
                <mi></mi>
                <mo>=3D</mo>
                <munder>
                  <mo movablelimits=3D"true" form=3D"prefix">lim</mo>
                  <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                    <mi>h</mi>
                    <mo stretchy=3D"false">=E2=86=92<!-- =E2=86=92 --></mo>
                    <mn>0</mn>
                  </mrow>
                </munder>
                <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                  <mfrac>
                    <mrow>
                      <mn>9</mn>
                      <mo>+</mo>
                      <mn>6</mn>
                      <mi>h</mi>
                      <mo>+</mo>
                      <msup>
                        <mi>h</mi>
                        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                          <mn>2</mn>
                        </mrow>
                      </msup>
                      <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
                      <mn>9</mn>
                    </mrow>
                    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                      <mi>h</mi>
                    </mrow>
                  </mfrac>
                </mrow>
              </mtd>
            </mtr>
            <mtr>
              <mtd></mtd>
              <mtd>
                <mi></mi>
                <mo>=3D</mo>
                <munder>
                  <mo movablelimits=3D"true" form=3D"prefix">lim</mo>
                  <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                    <mi>h</mi>
                    <mo stretchy=3D"false">=E2=86=92<!-- =E2=86=92 --></mo>
                    <mn>0</mn>
                  </mrow>
                </munder>
                <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                  <mfrac>
                    <mrow>
                      <mn>6</mn>
                      <mi>h</mi>
                      <mo>+</mo>
                      <msup>
                        <mi>h</mi>
                        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                          <mn>2</mn>
                        </mrow>
                      </msup>
                    </mrow>
                    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                      <mi>h</mi>
                    </mrow>
                  </mfrac>
                </mrow>
              </mtd>
            </mtr>
            <mtr>
              <mtd></mtd>
              <mtd>
                <mi></mi>
                <mo>=3D</mo>
                <munder>
                  <mo movablelimits=3D"true" form=3D"prefix">lim</mo>
                  <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                    <mi>h</mi>
                    <mo stretchy=3D"false">=E2=86=92<!-- =E2=86=92 --></mo>
                    <mn>0</mn>
                  </mrow>
                </munder>
                <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
                <mn>6</mn>
                <mo>+</mo>
                <mi>h</mi>
                <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
              </mtd>
            </mtr>
            <mtr>
              <mtd></mtd>
              <mtd>
                <mi></mi>
                <mo>=3D</mo>
                <mn>6</mn>
              </mtd>
            </mtr>
          </mtable>
        </mrow>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle {\begin{align=
ed}f'(3)&amp;=3D\lim _{h\to 0}{(3+h)^{2}-3^{2} \over {h}}\\&amp;=3D\lim _{h=
\to 0}{9+6h+h^{2}-9 \over {h}}\\&amp;=3D\lim _{h\to 0}{6h+h^{2} \over {h}}\=
\&amp;=3D\lim _{h\to 0}(6+h)\\&amp;=3D6\end{aligned}}}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/ac4f244e335714a06d06c32b6f91097d713615bf" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -12.171ex; width:29.203ex; height:25.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle =
{\begin{aligned}f'(3)&amp;=3D\lim _{h\to 0}{(3+h)^{2}-3^{2} \over {h}}\\&am=
p;=3D\lim _{h\to 0}{9+6h+h^{2}-9 \over {h}}\\&amp;=3D\lim _{h\to 0}{6h+h^{2=
} \over {h}}\\&amp;=3D\lim _{h\to 0}(6+h)\\&amp;=3D6\end{aligned}}}"></span=
></dd></dl>
<p>The slope of the tangent line to the squaring function at the point (3, =
9) is 6, that is to say, it is going up six times as fast as it is going to=
 the right. The limit process just described can be performed for any point=
 in the domain of the squaring function. This defines the <i>derivative fun=
ction</i> of the squaring function or just the <i>derivative</i> of the squ=
aring function for short. A computation similar to the one above shows that=
 the derivative of the squaring function is the doubling function.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-:4_52-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-:4-52"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>52<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap=
"><span title=3D"Page: 63">:=E2=80=8A63=E2=80=8A</span></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Leibniz_notation">Leibniz n=
otation</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leibniz%27s_notation=
" title=3D"Leibniz's notation">Leibniz's notation</a></div>
<p>A common notation, introduced by Leibniz, for the derivative in the exam=
ple above is
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e {\begin{aligned}y&amp;=3Dx^{2}\\{\frac {dy}{dx}}&amp;=3D2x.\end{aligned}}=
}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mtable columnalign=3D"right left right left right left right lef=
t right left right left" rowspacing=3D"3pt" columnspacing=3D"0em 2em 0em 2e=
m 0em 2em 0em 2em 0em 2em 0em" displaystyle=3D"true">
            <mtr>
              <mtd>
                <mi>y</mi>
              </mtd>
              <mtd>
                <mi></mi>
                <mo>=3D</mo>
                <msup>
                  <mi>x</mi>
                  <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                    <mn>2</mn>
                  </mrow>
                </msup>
              </mtd>
            </mtr>
            <mtr>
              <mtd>
                <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                  <mfrac>
                    <mrow>
                      <mi>d</mi>
                      <mi>y</mi>
                    </mrow>
                    <mrow>
                      <mi>d</mi>
                      <mi>x</mi>
                    </mrow>
                  </mfrac>
                </mrow>
              </mtd>
              <mtd>
                <mi></mi>
                <mo>=3D</mo>
                <mn>2</mn>
                <mi>x</mi>
                <mo>.</mo>
              </mtd>
            </mtr>
          </mtable>
        </mrow>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle {\begin{align=
ed}y&amp;=3Dx^{2}\\{\frac {dy}{dx}}&amp;=3D2x.\end{aligned}}}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/071de0d7365a25822c9ff04f42b1e71a22969eaa" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -3.838ex; width:10.371ex; height:8.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle {\=
begin{aligned}y&amp;=3Dx^{2}\\{\frac {dy}{dx}}&amp;=3D2x.\end{aligned}}}"><=
/span></dd></dl>
<p>In an approach based on limits, the symbol <span class=3D"texhtml"><span=
 class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num"><i>dy</i=
></span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"den"><i> dx</i></spa=
n></span>=E2=81=A0</span></span> is to be interpreted not as the quotient o=
f two numbers but as a shorthand for the limit computed above.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-:4_52-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Calculus#cite_note-:4-52"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>52<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><spa=
n title=3D"Page: 74">:=E2=80=8A74=E2=80=8A</span></sup> Leibniz, however, d=
id intend it to represent the quotient of two infinitesimally small numbers=
, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>dy</i></span> being the infinitesimally small =
change in <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>y</i></span> caused by an infinitesima=
lly small change <span class=3D"texhtml"><i> dx</i></span> applied to <span=
 class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i></span>. We can also think of <span class=3D"tex=
html"><link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateSt=
yles:r1214402035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span=
 class=3D"num"><i>d</i></span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=
=3D"den"><i> dx</i></span></span>=E2=81=A0</span></span> as a differentiati=
on operator, which takes a function as an input and gives another function,=
 the derivative, as the output. For example:
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e {\frac {d}{dx}}(x^{2})=3D2x.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mi>d</mi>
            <mrow>
              <mi>d</mi>
              <mi>x</mi>
            </mrow>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <msup>
          <mi>x</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>2</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mn>2</mn>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle {\frac {d}{dx=
}}(x^{2})=3D2x.}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/6c4fd3f805c38024f3887477b61fd2297f4e8050" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -2.005ex; width:13.812ex; height:5.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle {\=
frac {d}{dx}}(x^{2})=3D2x.}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>In this usage, the <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>dx</i></span> in the denom=
inator is read as "with respect to <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i></span>"=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:4_52-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-:4-52"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>52<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"referenc=
e nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 79">:=E2=80=8A79=E2=80=8A</span></sup> Anoth=
er example of correct notation could be:
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e {\begin{aligned}g(t)&amp;=3Dt^{2}+2t+4\\{d \over dt}g(t)&amp;=3D2t+2\end{=
aligned}}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mtable columnalign=3D"right left right left right left right lef=
t right left right left" rowspacing=3D"3pt" columnspacing=3D"0em 2em 0em 2e=
m 0em 2em 0em 2em 0em 2em 0em" displaystyle=3D"true">
            <mtr>
              <mtd>
                <mi>g</mi>
                <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
                <mi>t</mi>
                <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
              </mtd>
              <mtd>
                <mi></mi>
                <mo>=3D</mo>
                <msup>
                  <mi>t</mi>
                  <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                    <mn>2</mn>
                  </mrow>
                </msup>
                <mo>+</mo>
                <mn>2</mn>
                <mi>t</mi>
                <mo>+</mo>
                <mn>4</mn>
              </mtd>
            </mtr>
            <mtr>
              <mtd>
                <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                  <mfrac>
                    <mi>d</mi>
                    <mrow>
                      <mi>d</mi>
                      <mi>t</mi>
                    </mrow>
                  </mfrac>
                </mrow>
                <mi>g</mi>
                <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
                <mi>t</mi>
                <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
              </mtd>
              <mtd>
                <mi></mi>
                <mo>=3D</mo>
                <mn>2</mn>
                <mi>t</mi>
                <mo>+</mo>
                <mn>2</mn>
              </mtd>
            </mtr>
          </mtable>
        </mrow>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
