ed}g(t)&amp;=3Dt^{2}+2t+4\\{d \over dt}g(t)&amp;=3D2t+2\end{aligned}}}</ann=
otation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/3027f5cc71e051e302d6deccab3c362f53a30b1b" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -3.838ex; width:21.246ex; height:8.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle {\=
begin{aligned}g(t)&amp;=3Dt^{2}+2t+4\\{d \over dt}g(t)&amp;=3D2t+2\end{alig=
ned}}}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>Even when calculus is developed using limits rather than infinitesimals,=
 it is common to manipulate symbols like <span class=3D"texhtml"><i> dx</i>=
</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>dy</i></span> as if they were real n=
umbers; although it is possible to avoid such manipulations, they are somet=
imes notationally convenient in expressing operations such as the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Total_derivative" title=3D"Total derivati=
ve">total derivative</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Integral_calculus">Integral=
 calculus</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integral" title=3D"I=
ntegral">Integral</a></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1273380762/mw-parser-output/.tmulti"><div class=3D"thumb tmulti tright"><di=
v class=3D"thumbinner multiimageinner" style=3D"width:292px;max-width:292px=
"><div class=3D"trow"><div class=3D"tsingle" style=3D"width:290px;max-width=
:290px"><div class=3D"thumbimage" style=3D"height:268px;overflow:hidden"><s=
pan typeof=3D"mw:File"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Integr=
al_as_region_under_curve.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img alt=3D"" s=
rc=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f2/Integral_as=
_region_under_curve.svg/330px-Integral_as_region_under_curve.svg.png" decod=
ing=3D"async" width=3D"288" height=3D"269" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-f=
ile-width=3D"750" data-file-height=3D"700"></a></span></div><div class=3D"t=
humbcaption">Integration can be thought of as measuring the area under a cu=
rve, defined by <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i>(<i>x</i>)</span>, between =
two points (here <span class=3D"texhtml"><i> a</i></span> and <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i></span>).</div></div></div><div class=3D"trow"><div cl=
ass=3D"tsingle" style=3D"width:290px;max-width:290px"><div class=3D"thumbim=
age" style=3D"height:154px;overflow:hidden"><span typeof=3D"mw:File"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Riemann_integral_regular.gif" class=
=3D"mw-file-description"><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/=
wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/28/Riemann_integral_regular.gif/330px-Riemann_int=
egral_regular.gif" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"288" height=3D"155" class=3D=
"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"558" data-file-height=3D"300"></a></sp=
an></div><div class=3D"thumbcaption">A sequence of midpoint Riemann sums ov=
er a regular partition of an interval: the total area of the rectangles con=
verges to the integral of the function.</div></div></div></div></div>
<p><i>Integral calculus</i> is the study of the definitions, properties, an=
d applications of two related concepts, the <i>indefinite integral</i> and =
the <i>definite integral</i>. The process of finding the value of an integr=
al is called <i>integration</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:5_50-2" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-:5-50"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>50<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 508">:=E2=80=
=8A508=E2=80=8A</span></sup> The indefinite integral, also known as the <i>=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antiderivative" title=3D"Antideriv=
ative">antiderivative</a></i>, is the inverse operation to the derivative.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-:4_52-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-:4-52"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>52<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference =
nowrap"><span title=3D"Pages: 163=E2=80=93165">:=E2=80=8A163=E2=80=93165=E2=
=80=8A</span></sup> <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>F</i></span> is an indefinit=
e integral of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i></span> when <span class=3D"t=
exhtml"><i>f</i></span> is a derivative of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>F</i>=
</span>. (This use of lower- and upper-case letters for a function and its =
indefinite integral is common in calculus.) The definite integral inputs a =
function and outputs a number, which gives the algebraic sum of areas betwe=
en the graph of the input and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
X-axis" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"X-axis">x-axis</a>. The technical de=
finition of the definite integral involves the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Limit_(mathematics)" title=3D"Limit (mathematics)">limit</a> o=
f a sum of areas of rectangles, called a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Riemann_sum" title=3D"Riemann sum">Riemann sum</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-:2_53-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ca=
lculus#cite_note-:2-53"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>53<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span t=
itle=3D"Page: 282">:=E2=80=8A282=E2=80=8A</span></sup>
</p><p>A motivating example is the distance traveled in a given time.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-:4_52-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-:4-52"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>52<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowra=
p"><span title=3D"Pages: 153">:=E2=80=8A153=E2=80=8A</span></sup> If the sp=
eed is constant, only multiplication is needed:
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e \mathrm {Distance} =3D\mathrm {Speed} \cdot \mathrm {Time} }">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">D</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">i</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">s</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">t</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">a</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">n</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">c</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">e</mi>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">S</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">p</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">e</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">e</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">d</mi>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=E2=8B=85<!-- =E2=8B=85 --></mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">T</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">i</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">m</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">e</mi>
        </mrow>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \mathrm {Dist=
ance} =3D\mathrm {Speed} \cdot \mathrm {Time} }</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/6a2a54be44a458fc96b0fe0083ed6dc1a4f7da48" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.671ex; width:24.776ex; height:2.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \m=
athrm {Distance} =3D\mathrm {Speed} \cdot \mathrm {Time} }"></span></dd></d=
l>
<p>But if the speed changes, a more powerful method of finding the distance=
 is necessary. One such method is to approximate the distance traveled by b=
reaking up the time into many short intervals of time, then multiplying the=
 time elapsed in each interval by one of the speeds in that interval, and t=
hen taking the sum (a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Riemann_sum"=
 title=3D"Riemann sum">Riemann sum</a>) of the approximate distance travele=
d in each interval. The basic idea is that if only a short time elapses, th=
en the speed will stay more or less the same. However, a Riemann sum only g=
ives an approximation of the distance traveled. We must take the limit of a=
ll such Riemann sums to find the exact distance traveled.
</p><p>When velocity is constant, the total distance traveled over the give=
n time interval can be computed by multiplying velocity and time. For examp=
le, traveling a steady 50&nbsp;mph for 3 hours results in a total distance =
of 150 miles. Plotting the velocity as a function of time yields a rectangl=
e with a height equal to the velocity and a width equal to the time elapsed=
. Therefore, the product of velocity and time also calculates the rectangul=
ar area under the (constant) velocity curve.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:5_50-3" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_no=
te-:5-50"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>50<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page / =
location: 535">:=E2=80=8A535=E2=80=8A</span></sup> This connection between =
the area under a curve and the distance traveled can be extended to <i>any<=
/i> irregularly shaped region exhibiting a fluctuating velocity over a give=
n period. If <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i>(<i>x</i>)</span> represents s=
peed as it varies over time, the distance traveled between the times repres=
ented by <span class=3D"texhtml"><i> a</i></span> and <span class=3D"texhtm=
l"><i>b</i></span> is the area of the region between <span class=3D"texhtml=
"><i>f</i>(<i>x</i>)</span> and the <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i></span>=
-axis, between <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i> =3D <i>a</i></span> and <sp=
an class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i> =3D <i>b</i></span>.
</p><p>To approximate that area, an intuitive method would be to divide up =
the distance between <span class=3D"texhtml"><i> a</i></span> and <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i></span> into several equal segments, the length of e=
ach segment represented by the symbol <span class=3D"texhtml">=CE=94<i>x</i=
></span>. For each small segment, we can choose one value of the function <=
span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i>(<i>x</i>)</span>. Call that value <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml"><i>h</i></span>. Then the area of the rectangle with base <s=
pan class=3D"texhtml">=CE=94<i>x</i></span> and height <span class=3D"texht=
ml"><i>h</i></span> gives the distance (time <span class=3D"texhtml">=CE=94=
<i>x</i></span> multiplied by speed <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>h</i></span>=
) traveled in that segment. Associated with each segment is the average val=
ue of the function above it, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i>(<i>x</i>) =3D=
 <i>h</i></span>. The sum of all such rectangles gives an approximation of =
the area between the axis and the curve, which is an approximation of the t=
otal distance traveled. A smaller value for <span class=3D"texhtml">=CE=94<=
i>x</i></span> will give more rectangles and in most cases a better approxi=
mation, but for an exact answer, we need to take a limit as <span class=3D"=
texhtml">=CE=94<i>x</i></span> approaches zero.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:5_50-4"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite=
_note-:5-50"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>50<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page=
 / location: 512=E2=80=93522">:=E2=80=8A512=E2=80=93522=E2=80=8A</span></su=
p>
</p><p>The symbol of integration is <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-mat=
h-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11=
y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/Math=
ML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle \int }">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mo>=E2=88=AB<!-- =E2=88=AB --></mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \int }</annot=
ation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/ca732e5519cd2210bd59f1ab281b4e8f5a6a4413" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -2.338ex; width:2.194ex; height:5.676ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \in=
t }"></span>, an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Long_s" title=3D"=
Long s">elongated <i>S</i></a> chosen to suggest summation.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-:5_50-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C=
alculus#cite_note-:5-50"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>50<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span t=
itle=3D"Pages: 529">:=E2=80=8A529=E2=80=8A</span></sup> The definite integr=
al is written as:
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e \int _{a}^{b}f(x)\,dx}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msubsup>
          <mo>=E2=88=AB<!-- =E2=88=AB --></mo>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>a</mi>
          </mrow>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>b</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msubsup>
        <mi>f</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mspace width=3D"thinmathspace"></mspace>
        <mi>d</mi>
        <mi>x</mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \int _{a}^{b}=
f(x)\,dx}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/ac02adeed584466d53dee65f3228ad66939eb58b" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -2.338ex; width:11.139ex; height:6.343ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \i=
nt _{a}^{b}f(x)\,dx}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>and is read "the integral from <i>a</i> to <i>b</i> of <i>f</i>-of-<i>x<=
/i> with respect to <i>x</i>." The Leibniz notation <span class=3D"texhtml"=
><i>dx</i></span> is intended to suggest dividing the area under the curve =
into an infinite number of rectangles so that their width <span class=3D"te=
xhtml">=CE=94<i>x</i></span> becomes the infinitesimally small <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>dx</i></span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-TMU_34-3" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-TMU-34"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page / location: 44=
">:=E2=80=8A44=E2=80=8A</span></sup>
</p><p>The indefinite integral, or antiderivative, is written:
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e \int f(x)\,dx.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mo>=E2=88=AB<!-- =E2=88=AB --></mo>
        <mi>f</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mspace width=3D"thinmathspace"></mspace>
        <mi>d</mi>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \int f(x)\,dx=
.}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/fbbae4f208c1a8c2f6ed7a0cee104f8710e39dee" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -2.338ex; width:10.578ex; height:5.676ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \i=
nt f(x)\,dx.}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>Functions differing by only a constant have the same derivative, and it =
can be shown that the antiderivative of a given function is a family of fun=
ctions differing only by a constant.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:2_53-1" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-:2-53=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>53<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 326">:=E2=
=80=8A326=E2=80=8A</span></sup> Since the derivative of the function <span =
class=3D"texhtml"><i>y</i> =3D <i>x</i><sup>2</sup> + <i>C</i></span>, wher=
e <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>C</i></span> is any constant, is <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>y=E2=80=B2</i> =3D 2<i>x</i></span>, the antiderivative of =
the latter is given by:
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e \int 2x\,dx=3Dx^{2}+C.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mo>=E2=88=AB<!-- =E2=88=AB --></mo>
        <mn>2</mn>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mspace width=3D"thinmathspace"></mspace>
        <mi>d</mi>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <msup>
          <mi>x</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>2</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
        <mo>+</mo>
        <mi>C</mi>
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \int 2x\,dx=
=3Dx^{2}+C.}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/20b5d8e0b09ed96af70a130b188f2058c9f0324a" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -2.338ex; width:18.742ex; height:5.676ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \i=
nt 2x\,dx=3Dx^{2}+C.}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>The unspecified constant <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>C</i></span> present=
 in the indefinite integral or antiderivative is known as the <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Constant_of_integration" title=3D"Constant of i=
ntegration">constant of integration</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-54" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-54"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>54<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page / location: 13=
5">:=E2=80=8A135=E2=80=8A</span></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Fundamental_theorem">Fundam=
ental theorem</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fundamental_theorem_=
of_calculus" title=3D"Fundamental theorem of calculus">Fundamental theorem =
of calculus</a></div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fundamental_theorem_of_calc=
ulus" title=3D"Fundamental theorem of calculus">fundamental theorem of calc=
ulus</a> states that differentiation and integration are inverse operations=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:2_53-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-:2-53"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>53<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"referenc=
e nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 290">:=E2=80=8A290=E2=80=8A</span></sup> Mor=
e precisely, it relates the values of antiderivatives to definite integrals=
. Because it is usually easier to compute an antiderivative than to apply t=
he definition of a definite integral, the fundamental theorem of calculus p=
rovides a practical way of computing definite integrals. It can also be int=
erpreted as a precise statement of the fact that differentiation is the inv=
erse of integration.
</p><p>The fundamental theorem of calculus states: If a function <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i></span> is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C=
ontinuous_function" title=3D"Continuous function">continuous</a> on the int=
erval <span class=3D"texhtml">[<i>a</i>, <i>b</i>]</span> and if <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml"><i>F</i></span> is a function whose derivative is <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i></span> on the interval <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>a<=
/i>, <i>b</i>)</span>, then
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e \int _{a}^{b}f(x)\,dx=3DF(b)-F(a).}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msubsup>
          <mo>=E2=88=AB<!-- =E2=88=AB --></mo>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>a</mi>
          </mrow>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>b</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msubsup>
        <mi>f</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mspace width=3D"thinmathspace"></mspace>
        <mi>d</mi>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mi>F</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>b</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
        <mi>F</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>a</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \int _{a}^{b}=
f(x)\,dx=3DF(b)-F(a).}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/4f470e7743fda04c3d353a4dee2f441ae454f528" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -2.338ex; width:27.052ex; height:6.343ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \i=
nt _{a}^{b}f(x)\,dx=3DF(b)-F(a).}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>Furthermore, for every <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i></span> in the in=
terval <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>a</i>, <i>b</i>)</span>,
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e {\frac {d}{dx}}\int _{a}^{x}f(t)\,dt=3Df(x).}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mi>d</mi>
            <mrow>
              <mi>d</mi>
              <mi>x</mi>
            </mrow>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
        <msubsup>
          <mo>=E2=88=AB<!-- =E2=88=AB --></mo>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>a</mi>
          </mrow>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>x</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msubsup>
        <mi>f</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>t</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mspace width=3D"thinmathspace"></mspace>
        <mi>d</mi>
        <mi>t</mi>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mi>f</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle {\frac {d}{dx=
}}\int _{a}^{x}f(t)\,dt=3Df(x).}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/bf4f64cc882e88a4d7b634c37b7c1684630c3687" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -2.338ex; width:22.325ex; height:5.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle {\=
frac {d}{dx}}\int _{a}^{x}f(t)\,dt=3Df(x).}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>This realization, made by both <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Isaac_Newton" title=3D"Isaac Newton">Newton</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Gottfried_Leibniz" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Gottfri=
ed Leibniz">Leibniz</a>, was key to the proliferation of analytic results a=
fter their work became known. (The extent to which Newton and Leibniz were =
influenced by immediate predecessors, and particularly what Leibniz may hav=
e learned from the work of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isaac_B=
arrow" title=3D"Isaac Barrow">Isaac Barrow</a>, is difficult to determine b=
ecause of the priority dispute between them.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-55" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-=
55"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>55<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup>) The fundamental theorem provides an algebraic method of co=
mputing many definite integrals=E2=80=94without performing limit processes=
=E2=80=94by finding formulae for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A=
ntiderivative" title=3D"Antiderivative">antiderivatives</a>. It is also a p=
rototype solution of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Differentia=
l_equation" title=3D"Differential equation">differential equation</a>. Diff=
erential equations relate an unknown function to its derivatives and are ub=
iquitous in the sciences.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-56" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-56"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>56<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup c=
lass=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Pages: 351=E2=80=93352">:=E2=80=8A=
351=E2=80=93352=E2=80=8A</span></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Applications">Applications<=
/h2></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:NautilusCutawayLogarithmicSpi=
ral.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia=
.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/08/NautilusCutawayLogarithmicSpiral.jpg/250p=
x-NautilusCutawayLogarithmicSpiral.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" he=
ight=3D"189" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"2240" data-file-h=
eight=3D"1693"></a><figcaption>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Logarithmic_spiral" title=3D"Logarithmic spiral">logarithmic spiral</a> of=
 the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nautilus" title=3D"Nautilus">=
nautilus shell</a> is a classical image used to depict the growth and chang=
e related to calculus.</figcaption></figure>
<p>Calculus is used in every branch of the physical sciences,<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-57" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calc=
ulus#cite_note-57"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>57<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=
=3D"Page: 1">:=E2=80=8A1=E2=80=8A</span></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Actuarial_science" title=3D"Actuarial science">actuarial scien=
ce</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_science" title=3D=
"Computer science">computer science</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Statistics" title=3D"Statistics">statistics</a>, <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Engineering" title=3D"Engineering">engineering</a>, <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Economics" title=3D"Economics">econ=
omics</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Business" title=3D"Busi=
ness">business</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Medicine" titl=
e=3D"Medicine">medicine</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Demog=
raphy" title=3D"Demography">demography</a>, and in other fields wherever a =
problem can be <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_model"=
 title=3D"Mathematical model">mathematically modeled</a> and an <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Optimization_(mathematics)" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Optimization (mathematics)">optimal</a> solution is desired. =
It allows one to go from (non-constant) rates of change to the total change=
 or vice versa, and many times in studying a problem we know one and are tr=
ying to find the other.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-58" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-58"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>58<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Calcul=
us can be used in conjunction with other mathematical disciplines. For exam=
ple, it can be used with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_al=
gebra" title=3D"Linear algebra">linear algebra</a> to find the "best fit" l=
inear approximation for a set of points in a domain. Or, it can be used in =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_theory" title=3D"Proba=
bility theory">probability theory</a> to determine the <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Expectation_value" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Expe=
ctation value">expectation value</a> of a continuous <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_variable" title=3D"Random variable">random variab=
le</a> given a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_density=
_function" title=3D"Probability density function">probability density funct=
ion</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-59" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-59"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>59<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference=
 nowrap"><span title=3D"Page / location: 37">:=E2=80=8A37=E2=80=8A</span></=
sup> In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_geometry" title=
=3D"Analytic geometry">analytic geometry</a>, the study of graphs of functi=
ons, calculus is used to find high points and low points (maxima and minima=
), slope, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Concave_function" title=
=3D"Concave function">concavity</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Inflection_points" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Inflection points">=
inflection points</a>. Calculus is also used to find approximate solutions =
to equations; in practice, it is the standard way to solve differential equ=
ations and do root finding in most applications. Examples are methods such =
as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Newton%27s_method" title=3D"New=
ton's method">Newton's method</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Fixed_point_iteration" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Fixed point iteratio=
n">fixed point iteration</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Linear_approximation" title=3D"Linear approximation">linear approximation</=
a>. For instance, spacecraft use a variation of the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Euler_method" title=3D"Euler method">Euler method</a> to =
approximate curved courses within zero-gravity environments.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Physics" title=3D"Physics">=
Physics</a> makes particular use of calculus; all concepts in <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Classical_mechanics" title=3D"Classical mechani=
cs">classical mechanics</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/El=
ectromagnetism" title=3D"Electromagnetism">electromagnetism</a> are related=
 through calculus. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mass" title=
=3D"Mass">mass</a> of an object of known <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Density" title=3D"Density">density</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Moment_of_inertia" title=3D"Moment of inertia">moment of i=
nertia</a> of objects, and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pot=
ential_energy" title=3D"Potential energy">potential energies</a> due to gra=
vitational and electromagnetic forces can all be found by the use of calcul=
us. An example of the use of calculus in mechanics is <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Newton%27s_laws_of_motion" title=3D"Newton's laws of mo=
tion">Newton's second law of motion</a>, which states that the derivative o=
f an object's <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Momentum" title=3D"M=
omentum">momentum</a> concerning time equals the net <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Force" title=3D"Force">force</a> upon it. Alternatively,=
 Newton's second law can be expressed by saying that the net force equals t=
he object's mass times its <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acceler=
ation" title=3D"Acceleration">acceleration</a>, which is the time derivativ=
e of velocity and thus the second time derivative of spatial position. Star=
ting from knowing how an object is accelerating, we use calculus to derive =
its path.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-60" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-60"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>60<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Maxwell's theory of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electro=
magnetism" title=3D"Electromagnetism">electromagnetism</a> and <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Albert_Einstein" title=3D"Albert Einstein">Ein=
stein</a>'s theory of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/General_rela=
tivity" title=3D"General relativity">general relativity</a> are also expres=
sed in the language of differential calculus.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-61" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-=
61"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>61<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-62" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-62"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>62<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"re=
ference nowrap"><span title=3D"Pages: 52=E2=80=9355">:=E2=80=8A52=E2=80=935=
5=E2=80=8A</span></sup> Chemistry also uses calculus in determining reactio=
n rates<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:3_63-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-:3-63"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>63<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"re=
ference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 599">:=E2=80=8A599=E2=80=8A</span></su=
p> and in studying radioactive decay.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:3_63-1" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-:3-6=
3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>63<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 814">:=
=E2=80=8A814=E2=80=8A</span></sup> In biology, population dynamics starts w=
ith reproduction and death rates to model population changes.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-64" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calc=
ulus#cite_note-64"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>64<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-65" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-65"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>65<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
<sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 631">:=E2=80=8A631=E2=
=80=8A</span></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Green%27s_theorem" title=3D=
"Green's theorem">Green's theorem</a>, which gives the relationship between=
 a line integral around a simple closed curve C and a double integral over =
the plane region D bounded by C, is applied in an instrument known as a <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Planimeter" title=3D"Planimeter">plan=
imeter</a>, which is used to calculate the area of a flat surface on a draw=
ing.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-66" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-66"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6=
6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> For example, it can be use=
d to calculate the amount of area taken up by an irregularly shaped flower =
bed or swimming pool when designing the layout of a piece of property.
</p><p>In the realm of medicine, calculus can be used to find the optimal b=
ranching angle of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blood_vessel" =
title=3D"Blood vessel">blood vessel</a> to maximize flow.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-67" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus=
#cite_note-67"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>67<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup> Calculus can be applied to understand how quickl=
y a drug is eliminated from a body or how quickly a <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Cancer" title=3D"Cancer">cancerous</a> tumor grows.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-68" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Calculus#cite_note-68"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>68<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In economics, calculus allows for the determination of maximal profi=
t by providing a way to easily calculate both <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Marginal_cost" title=3D"Marginal cost">marginal cost</a> and <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marginal_revenue" title=3D"Marginal =
revenue">marginal revenue</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-69" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus#cite_note-69"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>69<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
<sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 387">:=E2=80=8A387=E2=
=80=8A</span></sup>
</p>
